1.1. Density plot showing the basic statistics:

Mean (red), median (green), standard deviation, minimum (purple) and maximum (black)

In [44]:
 df = car_sales['Sales_in_thousands'].plot(kind='density', figsize=(7,7))
df.axvline(car_sales['Sales_in_thousands'].mean(), color='red')
df.axvline(car_sales['Sales_in_thousands'].median(), color='green')
df.axvline(car_sales['Sales_in_thousands'].max(), color='black')
df.axvline(car_sales['Sales_in_thousands'].min(), color='purple')
df.axvline(car_sales['Sales_in_thousands'].std(), color='blue')
plt.title("Density Plot Showing  the Basic Statistics of Sales in Thousands for the Car Sales Data")
plt.xlabel('Sales in Thousands')
plt.ylabel('Density')
Out[44]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Density')

The plot above gives a quick view and summary of the basic statistics of the sales:

  • The average of the sales is 52.998 (red line), with a median sales value of 29.450 (green line)
  • The maximum (black line) and minimum sales are 540.561 and 0.110 respectively.
  • The sales has a standard deviation SD of 68.029 (blue line) and this shows that the sales is not that dispersed because it is close to the mean.

Out[25]:

  • The sum of sales in thousands of the passenger vehicle type was 5015.184 and that of the car vehicle type 3305.514 repectively.
  • The standard deviation shows that the sales in thousands of the car vehicle type is more dispersed around it's mean as compared to the dispersion of that of the passenger vehicle type.
  • The car vehicle type also has higher minimum 9.126 thousands and maximum 540.561 thousands compared to that of the passenger vehicle type with minimum 0.11 thousands and maximum 247.994 thousands.
  • The car sale vehicle type has fewer outliers than the passenger vehicle type.

7. Relationship between the length of the wheelbase and sales

In [30]:
sns.scatterplot(x = 'Wheelbase', y = 'Sales_in_thousands', data = car_sales, hue ='Vehicle_type')
Out[30]:
<Axes: xlabel='Wheelbase', ylabel='Sales_in_thousands'>

The wheelbase determines the comfort ratio of the ride because it affects the weight balance, handling, ride quality and steering of the vehicle. From the plot above,

  • The desire for comfort (longer wheelbase) did not really have much of an impact on sales of passenger vehicles but has more of an impact in the sales of car vehicles.

10. Conclusion

  • From the car sales data, the average sales is 52.998 and a standard deviation of 68.029 (all in thousands) which tells us that the data is not very dispersed or widely spread from the mean.
  • All data points below -66.649 and above 148.719 are outliers
  • Passenger and car vehicle types sold more when prices were below 50 thousand unlike when prices were above. Also passenger vehicles sold more than car vehicles when prices were above 50 thousand.
  • The standard deviation shows that the data of the sales of the car vehicle is more spread out from its mean as compared to that of the passenger vehicle.
  • More sales were made from the sales of passenger vehicles compared to car vehicles.
  • The average sales of car vehicles is higher than that of the passenger vehicles.
  • The highest selling manufacturers were Dodge and Ford.
  • The lowest selling were the Infiniti and Jaguar.
  • The desire for comfort (longer wheelbase) did not really have much of an impact on sales of passenger vehicles but has more of an impact in the sales of car vehicles.
  • There was no obvious relationship between increase/reduction in horsepower with sales
